rick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Hatton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Gilbert Aton 1st Baron Aton was born in 1288, in West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Aton II, was 38 and his mother, Isabel de Vere, was 30. He had at least 1 son with Alice De Aton. In 1350, at the age of 62, his occupation is listed as knight in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He died after 10 April 1350."},"et":{